For both approaches described in this Section 9 and Section 7, the continuous time data represented by the mathematics here must be time-warped or de-warped to achieve the indicated time-warping compensation in Eq. 31a or de-warping in Eq. 25 in order to evaluate the gradient at every iteration of the iterative gradient-ascent search method described in Section 10. Assuming that time-sampled data is used in the search algorithm for optimization described in the Section 10, the re-warping is implemented by re-interpolating the data. The computation and storage cost here depend significantly on the amount of data being processed. Using the minimum time-sampling rate 4Bx, that avoids overlap of both aliased cycles and aliased spectral components, and a time-bandwidth product of BxT=200\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
